AGI - The U.S. government has announced that it will review $9 billion of funding for Harvard University following anti-Semitism charges on campus. The decision follows the cut of millions of dollars already imposed at Columbia University, also the scene of strong student protests in favour of Palestine.
<h2> Trump's hard line
President Donald Trump> has embarked on a tough line against elite universities involved in fierce demonstrations, which broke out after the war between Israel and Hamas in Gaza. He revoked federal funding to these institutions and ordered immigration authorities to expel foreign students involved in protests, including those in possession of the green card.
Examination of contracts
According to a statement by the General Services Administration, officials will examine contracts for a total of 255.6 million dollars > between Harvard and the government, along with 8.7 billion dollars > in multiannual financing commitments.
<h2>Critics and support
Critics accuse Trump administration of carrying out a punitive campaign that could have a dissuasive effect on freedom of expression, while advocates are convinced that it is necessary to restore order on campuses and protect Jewish students.
Official statements
The Education Secretary, Linda McMahon>, said: "Harbor's failure to protect students on campus from anti-Semitic discrimination, all while promoting divisive ideologies at the expense of free research, seriously jeopardized his reputation." &nbsp;
"Harvard - he added - can correct these errors and return to being a campus dedicated to academic excellence and the search for truth, where all students feel safe."
<h2> The Harvard answer
In a note, Harvard President Alan Garner> said: "If this funding is suspended, life-saving research will be stopped and scientific innovation will be jeopardized." He also specified that "the government has informed us that it is evaluating this measure because it believes that the University has failed to fulfil its obligations of contrast and prevention of anti-Semitic harassment". Garner challenged this interpretation, stating that the athenaeus "strengthened its rules and disciplinary approach to those who violate them" in the last 15 months, precisely to address the issue of anti-Semitism on campus.
